data.TAXON_REMARKS: Shell up to 20 mm in height, distinct spiral ridges on whorls separated by narrow grooves, ridges sometimes flattened. Outer lip of aperture joins body whorl at about a right angle. Background shell colour may be white, yellow or reddish-brown, tessellated shells rare. The grooves are clearly pigmented (purplish-brown) in some populations, while in others the pigmentation may be faint or absent. When pigmentation absent, confusion with L. saxatilis may result.

data.TAXON_REMARKS: common periwinkle - Shell with faint spiral lines on whorls but surface generally smooth, apex pointed, up to 30 mm in height. Outer lip of aperture joins body whorl tangentially. Dark grey or black in colour, occasional specimens red, columella white. In small specimens inner surface of outer lip has alternate light and dark bands. Tentacles with black transverse bands.

data.TAXON_REMARKS: Shell with pronounced spire, up to 17 mm in height. Whorls with spiral ridges. Outer lip of aperture joins body whorl at about a right angle. It is almost impossible to distinguish the shells of L. arcana from those of L. saxatilis. Aperture large. Colour highly varied, whitish, yellow, brown to dark brown almost black, sometimes banded or tessellated.

data.TAXON_REMARKS: rough periwinkle - Shell with pronounced spire, up to 18 mm in height, but generally smaller. Whorls with spiral ridges. Outer lip of aperture joins body whorl at about a right angle. Colour varied, yellowish-white, greenish, reddish, brown, sometimes banded, tessellated. 'Wave' ecotype occurs on exposed cliffs and headlands (Johannesson et al. 2010).

Outer lip of aperture joins body whorl at about a right angle. Colour varied, yellowish-white, greenish, reddish, brown, sometimes banded, tessellated. Research using molecular techniques suggests that L. neglecta is not a distinct species but is an ecotype of L. saxatilis that occurs in low-shore barnacle zones.
